00:01:51.458 --> 00:01:52.500
the weather is very good.

00:01:52.500 --> 00:01:52.990
NATE GANA: It's fantastic.

00:01:52.990 --> 00:01:54.670
IAN CHANG: And the
food is good, as well.

00:01:54.670 --> 00:01:55.930
NATE GANA: The food
is very good, yes.

00:01:55.930 --> 00:01:56.430
Yes.

00:01:56.430 --> 00:01:58.530
Spain is one of my
favorite places to be.

00:01:58.530 --> 00:02:03.070
But tell me about how this
came about, Kavalan in general.

00:02:03.070 --> 00:02:06.870
IAN CHANG: So as Josh
mentioned just now,

00:02:06.870 --> 00:02:10.350
Kavalan started in 2005.

00:02:10.350 --> 00:02:14.730
At that time, we were the one
and only whisky distillery.

00:02:14.730 --> 00:02:17.880
So like our Japanese
neighbor, where

00:02:17.880 --> 00:02:21.480
they have Suntory, which
started the Japanese whisky

00:02:21.480 --> 00:02:25.740
industry back in 1923.

00:02:25.740 --> 00:02:28.740
Kavalan actually started the
Taiwanese whisky industry,

00:02:28.740 --> 00:02:31.950
but as late as 2006.

00:02:31.950 --> 00:02:34.920
But the reason for that, it
was actually quite simple.

00:02:34.920 --> 00:02:40.320
Because anytime before
2002, we couldn't

00:02:40.320 --> 00:02:43.980
have any private wineries,
distilleries, or breweries.

00:02:43.980 --> 00:02:44.730
NATE GANA: Really?

00:02:44.730 --> 00:02:46.770
IAN CHANG: Because of
the monopoly system

00:02:46.770 --> 00:02:49.210
that we used to have in Taiwan.

00:02:49.210 --> 00:02:51.600
So only our government
at that time

00:02:51.600 --> 00:02:56.860
could produce, import, and
also sell anything alcoholic.

00:02:56.860 --> 00:03:01.830
So Mr. Lee Sr., who is about
80 years old this year,

00:03:01.830 --> 00:03:05.880
he was really frustrated when
he was a young man 40 years ago,

00:03:05.880 --> 00:03:07.920
when he wanted to set
up his own distillery,

00:03:07.920 --> 00:03:09.750
but he couldn't do so.

00:03:09.750 --> 00:03:13.560
And that's why we waited
for almost 30 years.

00:03:13.560 --> 00:03:16.890
In 2002, finally,
the whole regulation

00:03:16.890 --> 00:03:19.410
was changed due to WTO.

00:03:19.410 --> 00:03:23.460
Because once you
join WTO, you have

00:03:23.460 --> 00:03:26.880
to embrace fair
competition, and also you

00:03:26.880 --> 00:03:29.790
have to open yourself
up to the whole world.

00:03:29.790 --> 00:03:30.420
NATE GANA: Yes.

00:03:30.420 --> 00:03:34.950
IAN CHANG: So that's why when
Mr. Lee was really chuffed,

00:03:34.950 --> 00:03:38.430
so he quickly set
up a small team

00:03:38.430 --> 00:03:43.920
of engineers, folk
technologists, even architects,

00:03:43.920 --> 00:03:49.085
because he has to design
the shape of our distillery.

00:03:49.085 --> 00:03:49.710
NATE GANA: Yes.

00:03:49.710 --> 00:03:57.300
IAN CHANG: So we even came to
US, Canada, Japan, Scotland,

00:03:57.300 --> 00:04:00.060
and also Ireland to
gather information,

00:04:00.060 --> 00:04:04.020
and also to see how to set
up a distillery of our own

00:04:04.020 --> 00:04:05.290
in Taiwan.

00:04:05.290 --> 00:04:09.540
So between 2002
and also 2005 that

00:04:09.540 --> 00:04:12.840
was what we call the
intelligence gathering

00:04:12.840 --> 00:04:17.070
phase of the setting
up of the distillery.

00:04:17.070 --> 00:04:22.390
So finally in April 2005,
we started construction.

00:04:22.390 --> 00:04:22.890
And guess?

00:04:22.890 --> 00:04:26.910
What it took us only nine months
to build a whole distillery.

00:04:26.910 --> 00:04:27.610
NATE GANA: What?

00:04:27.610 --> 00:04:30.915
IAN CHANG: Which I was
told that it was a record.

00:04:30.915 --> 00:04:33.210
NATE GANA: I think it's a
record for a lot of things.

00:04:33.210 --> 00:04:34.002
IAN CHANG: Exactly.

00:04:34.002 --> 00:04:37.380
So as Mr. Lee senior
always describes,

00:04:37.380 --> 00:04:40.920
it's like having a baby
born in nine months' time.

00:04:40.920 --> 00:04:42.380
So that's his baby.

00:04:42.380 --> 00:04:44.040
NATE GANA: It is his
baby, absolutely.

00:04:44.040 --> 00:04:46.170
IAN CHANG: So ever
since then, we've

00:04:46.170 --> 00:04:49.960
been producing whisky 24 hours
a day, seven days a week,

00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:53.353
365 days a year,
nonstop until today.

00:04:53.353 --> 00:04:54.270
NATE GANA: Oh, my god.

00:04:54.270 --> 00:04:54.937
IAN CHANG: Yeah.

00:04:54.937 --> 00:04:58.345
NATE GANA: So speaking of the
distillery, when I went over

00:04:58.345 --> 00:05:00.720
there, I learned a lot of
things, and one thing I learned

00:05:00.720 --> 00:05:02.580
was that the second
most popular distillery

00:05:02.580 --> 00:05:06.460
in the world in Scotland
has about 150,000 visitors

00:05:06.460 --> 00:05:07.550
per year.

00:05:07.550 --> 00:05:09.367
You guys have a million
visitors a year?

00:05:09.367 --> 00:05:11.200
IAN CHANG: Approximately,
yes, that's right.

00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:13.090
NATE GANA: You are number
one by a long shot.

00:05:13.090 --> 00:05:14.710
IAN CHANG: But
also in a way, that

00:05:14.710 --> 00:05:16.720
shows you how alcoholic we are--

00:05:16.720 --> 00:05:18.910
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:18.910 --> 00:05:19.707
In Taiwan.

00:05:19.707 --> 00:05:20.290
NATE GANA: OK.

00:05:20.290 --> 00:05:20.860
That's true.

00:05:20.860 --> 00:05:21.360
That's true.

00:05:21.360 --> 00:05:26.390
IAN CHANG: Because among the one
million visitors, 80% domestic,

00:05:26.390 --> 00:05:27.950
20% foreign.

00:05:27.950 --> 00:05:28.950
NATE GANA: 80% domestic.

00:05:28.950 --> 00:05:29.440
IAN CHANG: That's right.

00:05:29.440 --> 00:05:29.770
NATE GANA: Wow.

00:05:29.770 --> 00:05:30.770
IAN CHANG: That's right.

00:05:30.770 --> 00:05:33.160
Our domestic
consumers, when they

00:05:33.160 --> 00:05:37.733
don't have anywhere else to go,
they come to our distillery.

00:05:37.733 --> 00:05:38.650
NATE GANA: Oh, my god.

00:05:38.650 --> 00:05:42.140
So then with the products
that you're creating,

00:05:42.140 --> 00:05:43.840
how did you get
into whisky making?

00:05:43.840 --> 00:05:48.447
IAN CHANG: So it was actually
by, I would say by fate.

00:05:48.447 --> 00:05:49.030
NATE GANA: OK.

00:05:49.030 --> 00:05:57.700
IAN CHANG: Because in 2004, no,
sorry, I should say early 2005.

00:05:57.700 --> 00:06:01.540
During that time, my
father, he was really ill.

00:06:01.540 --> 00:06:07.987
So my mom asked me to come home,
and to look after the family.

00:06:07.987 --> 00:06:09.570
NATE GANA: Where
were you at the time?

00:06:09.570 --> 00:06:14.630
IAN CHANG: I was actually doing
small businesses in China.

00:06:14.630 --> 00:06:15.460
NATE GANA: OK.

00:06:15.460 --> 00:06:18.220
IAN CHANG: So I
came back to Taiwan.

00:06:18.220 --> 00:06:21.370
We finished everything in China.

00:06:21.370 --> 00:06:23.450
And at that time, I
didn't know what to do.

00:06:23.450 --> 00:06:26.390
I was actually really panicking.

00:06:26.390 --> 00:06:31.710
So every day, I remember
from January to April,

00:06:31.710 --> 00:06:34.810
every day I was searching
on the internet,

00:06:34.810 --> 00:06:38.860
through Google as well,
looking for a job.

00:06:38.860 --> 00:06:43.300
And in Taiwan we have this
so-called 104 website,

00:06:43.300 --> 00:06:48.290
which is the website you go
to look for job vacancies.

00:06:48.290 --> 00:06:52.100
So one day I saw, it was
3 o'clock in the morning,

00:06:52.100 --> 00:06:52.960
I couldn't sleep.

00:06:52.960 --> 00:06:55.570
And I saw that King
Car Company, which

00:06:55.570 --> 00:06:59.050
is the group that
is behind Kavalan,

00:06:59.050 --> 00:07:04.120
they were looking for someone
to be a spirit researcher.

00:07:04.120 --> 00:07:06.700
So it wasn't quite
a blender yet.

00:07:06.700 --> 00:07:11.170
So I sent my CV, and three
weeks later, a gentleman

00:07:11.170 --> 00:07:13.270
whose name is Peter--

00:07:13.270 --> 00:07:17.140
he's the special assistant
to our chairman, Mr. Lee--

00:07:17.140 --> 00:07:20.650
he called me and he said, "are
you still looking for a job."

00:07:20.650 --> 00:07:24.760
I said, "yes, I'm
desperate for a job."

00:07:24.760 --> 00:07:30.100
So he said, "come
to our headquarter,

00:07:30.100 --> 00:07:33.820
and do interview,
and see how it goes."

00:07:33.820 --> 00:07:38.590
So the next day I went, and
the very first question he

00:07:38.590 --> 00:07:42.960
asked me was if I had
any previous experience

00:07:42.960 --> 00:07:48.160
in the whisky industry or any
alcoholic beverage industry.

00:07:48.160 --> 00:07:51.220
And as you can tell, I'm
a very honest person,

00:07:51.220 --> 00:07:52.420
and the answer was no.

00:07:52.420 --> 00:07:54.970
So I said no, and
I thought that was

00:07:54.970 --> 00:07:56.720
the end of the conversation.

00:07:56.720 --> 00:07:59.540
But then I did emphasize
to him that for the eight

00:07:59.540 --> 00:08:02.530
years studying in
the UK as a student,

00:08:02.530 --> 00:08:04.310
I was drinking
almost every night.

00:08:04.310 --> 00:08:05.880
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:05.880 --> 00:08:08.200
And that should count
as very much being

00:08:08.200 --> 00:08:09.490
part of the industry, as well.

00:08:09.490 --> 00:08:14.620
So he said, why
don't you take a test

00:08:14.620 --> 00:08:18.070
on your nose to see if
you can differentiate

00:08:18.070 --> 00:08:19.960
all of these flavors.

00:08:19.960 --> 00:08:23.800
As you know that when we drink
whisky, I would say the most--

00:08:23.800 --> 00:08:25.310
and they would agree with me--

00:08:25.310 --> 00:08:29.050
the most fascinating and also
interesting thing about whisky

00:08:29.050 --> 00:08:35.950
is that every distillery has its
own unique flavors, qualities,

00:08:35.950 --> 00:08:37.190
and so on.

00:08:37.190 --> 00:08:44.560
So in front of me I had 15
of the so-called whisky notes

00:08:44.560 --> 00:08:48.250
that you can expect
from single malt whisky.

00:08:48.250 --> 00:08:52.930
And the rule was very simple
I could only nose them once,

00:08:52.930 --> 00:08:56.210
and then you have to write
down the descriptors.

00:08:56.210 --> 00:09:01.480
So apparently I was very lucky
that I had the highest score.

00:09:01.480 --> 00:09:04.725
But also it was then I knew
that my nose actually works.

00:09:04.725 --> 00:09:06.280
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:06.280 --> 00:09:10.740
I could differentiate all these
different flavors from whiskys.

00:09:10.740 --> 00:09:11.740
NATE GANA: Right, right.

00:09:11.740 --> 00:09:14.510
IAN CHANG: And once
I joined the company,

00:09:14.510 --> 00:09:19.420
I was really lucky once again,
very fortunate that Mr. Lee,

00:09:19.420 --> 00:09:22.870
he sent me to
Scotland for two years

00:09:22.870 --> 00:09:29.440
to study with the world famous
whisky expert of Dr. Jim Swam.

00:09:29.440 --> 00:09:30.740
NATE GANA: Jim Swan.

00:09:30.740 --> 00:09:33.670
IAN CHANG: So for
two years that was he

00:09:33.670 --> 00:09:37.510
was the person who taught
me everything about whisky,

00:09:37.510 --> 00:09:39.640
and life in general as well.

00:09:39.640 --> 00:09:42.160
So he's my Mr. Miyagi in a way.

00:09:42.160 --> 00:09:42.785
NATE GANA: Yes.

00:09:42.785 --> 00:09:44.202
IAN CHANG: And I'm
the whisky kid.

00:09:44.202 --> 00:09:46.082
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:46.082 --> 00:09:47.540
NATE GANA: That's
an amazing story,

00:09:47.540 --> 00:09:49.355
because I know now that--

00:09:49.355 --> 00:09:50.980
I mean, I don't want
to say the number.

00:09:50.980 --> 00:09:54.970
But how many whiskies do
you taste per day now?

00:09:54.970 --> 00:09:58.960
IAN CHANG: So on a daily basis,
if I'm not traveling, which

00:09:58.960 --> 00:10:00.190
is very difficult these days.

00:10:00.190 --> 00:10:03.490
Because I always say to
our audience and consumer

00:10:03.490 --> 00:10:08.870
that these days I'm
more into the show biz--

00:10:08.870 --> 00:10:12.243
being a brand ambassador,
going around the world.

00:10:12.243 --> 00:10:12.910
NATE GANA: Yeah.

00:10:12.910 --> 00:10:14.035
IAN CHANG: To all tastings.

00:10:14.035 --> 00:10:18.250
But whenever I go back to
Taiwan, on a daily basis,

00:10:18.250 --> 00:10:24.418
I have to nose samples in a
range of between 200 to 400.

00:10:24.418 --> 00:10:25.210
NATE GANA: Per day?

00:10:25.210 --> 00:10:27.400
IAN CHANG: On a
daily basis, yes.

00:10:27.400 --> 00:10:32.290
Because I have to catch up
with when I'm not there,

00:10:32.290 --> 00:10:33.807
because the production
doesn't stop.

00:10:33.807 --> 00:10:34.390
NATE GANA: No.

00:10:34.390 --> 00:10:38.680
IAN CHANG: So every day we have
new batches of the new make,

00:10:38.680 --> 00:10:43.390
and also you have matured
products in the casks.

00:10:43.390 --> 00:10:44.050
NATE GANA: Yes.

00:10:44.050 --> 00:10:46.990
IAN CHANG: All
waiting to be nosed,

00:10:46.990 --> 00:10:50.260
to be determined
whether they are matured

00:10:50.260 --> 00:10:53.545
or not, or if we need to
do something differently.

00:10:53.545 --> 00:10:54.170
NATE GANA: Yes.

00:10:54.170 --> 00:10:57.670
IAN CHANG: For example,
transferring from refill

00:10:57.670 --> 00:11:00.747
cask to say port cask.

00:11:00.747 --> 00:11:01.330
NATE GANA: Yes

00:11:01.330 --> 00:11:02.560
IAN CHANG: And so on.

00:11:02.560 --> 00:11:05.080
So it's very interesting.

00:11:05.080 --> 00:11:07.420
Even though I have so
many samples to nose,

00:11:07.420 --> 00:11:09.820
but I never get tired.

00:11:09.820 --> 00:11:11.830
I would say it's the
best job in the world.

00:11:11.830 --> 00:11:12.910
NATE GANA: Absolutely the
best job in the world.

00:11:12.910 --> 00:11:14.170
IAN CHANG: If you like to drink.

00:11:14.170 --> 00:11:15.520
NATE GANA: If you
like to drink, yes.

00:11:15.520 --> 00:11:16.020
Yes.

00:11:16.020 --> 00:11:18.670
And so is Kavalan producing
any other products other

00:11:18.670 --> 00:11:19.810
than whisky?

00:11:19.810 --> 00:11:25.550
IAN CHANG: Yes, last
year 2018 in November,

00:11:25.550 --> 00:11:28.167
we launched our latest gin.

00:11:28.167 --> 00:11:29.500
NATE GANA: Wow, congratulations.

00:11:29.500 --> 00:11:31.780
IAN CHANG: So this is
our gin number one,

00:11:31.780 --> 00:11:35.290
and this year we are
working on gin number two.

00:11:35.290 --> 00:11:41.920
So in the future, as we talked
about just now before the talk,

00:11:41.920 --> 00:11:42.650
in the future.

00:11:42.650 --> 00:11:45.670
I think in addition
to whisky, Kavalan

00:11:45.670 --> 00:11:50.330
and we also do gin and also
some other alcoholic beverages

00:11:50.330 --> 00:11:50.830
as well.

00:11:50.830 --> 00:11:51.320
NATE GANA: Oh, wow.

00:11:51.320 --> 00:11:53.110
IAN CHANG: So these
are all the surprises

00:11:53.110 --> 00:11:56.805
that we have for our
consumers for the future.

00:11:56.805 --> 00:11:57.680
NATE GANA: Fantastic.

00:11:57.680 --> 00:11:59.410
Well, I know that
the Distillery Select

00:11:59.410 --> 00:12:00.735
is new to the American market.

00:12:00.735 --> 00:12:02.860
What was the purpose of
creating Distillery Select?

00:12:02.860 --> 00:12:04.750
IAN CHANG: Right, so
the Distillery Select,

00:12:04.750 --> 00:12:08.200
which is the one here, this
was also launched last year,

00:12:08.200 --> 00:12:09.720
similar time to our gin.

00:12:09.720 --> 00:12:11.560
NATE GANA: OK.

00:12:11.560 --> 00:12:14.950
IAN CHANG: I would say
this is the brand new entry

00:12:14.950 --> 00:12:19.510
level for any consumers who
wants to either try whisky

00:12:19.510 --> 00:12:23.620
in general for the first time or
try Kavalan for the first time.

00:12:23.620 --> 00:12:27.730
Because in the past,
Kavalan has always

00:12:27.730 --> 00:12:32.032
been described as quality
only and no quantity.

00:12:32.032 --> 00:12:32.740
NATE GANA: Right.

00:12:32.740 --> 00:12:35.230
IAN CHANG: Because
the consumers always

00:12:35.230 --> 00:12:38.320
say that Kavalan
is a bit pricey,

00:12:38.320 --> 00:12:46.540
but Mr. Lee knows that quality
is actually our number one

00:12:46.540 --> 00:12:47.170
priority.

00:12:47.170 --> 00:12:48.490
NATE GANA: Absolutely.

00:12:48.490 --> 00:12:51.900
IAN CHANG: But in order to have
a volume maker for Kavalan,

00:12:51.900 --> 00:12:55.647
for quantity, we need to
do something differently.

00:12:55.647 --> 00:12:56.230
NATE GANA: Yes

00:12:56.230 --> 00:12:59.370
IAN CHANG: In order to
bring down the cost so

00:12:59.370 --> 00:13:06.010
that the final end price for our
consumers can be competitive.

00:13:06.010 --> 00:13:09.855
For example here in
Chicago, at Binny's.

00:13:09.855 --> 00:13:10.480
NATE GANA: Yes.

00:13:10.480 --> 00:13:12.063
IAN CHANG: I saw
this one on the shelf

00:13:12.063 --> 00:13:15.155
for $49.99, which is, I think,
a very competitive price.

00:13:15.155 --> 00:13:16.780
NATE GANA: Reasonable
price point, yes.

00:13:16.780 --> 00:13:20.420
IAN CHANG: And even though
the price is competitive,

00:13:20.420 --> 00:13:22.558
we don't compromise
anything on the quality.

00:13:22.558 --> 00:13:23.600
NATE GANA: Quality, yeah.

00:13:23.600 --> 00:13:24.100
Absolutely.

00:13:24.100 --> 00:13:29.230
IAN CHANG: So what we do is
by using refill casks, which

00:13:29.230 --> 00:13:34.520
are casks that have been used
repeatedly for many years.

00:13:34.520 --> 00:13:40.180
Some can be as old as
40 to 60 years old.

00:13:40.180 --> 00:13:43.900
But the thing is, once again,
because of the location

00:13:43.900 --> 00:13:50.590
of Taiwan, which is subtropical,
in our very hot summertime,

00:13:50.590 --> 00:13:53.110
the heat actually
managed to push

00:13:53.110 --> 00:13:58.270
more wood related flavors and
also colors into the whisky.

00:13:58.270 --> 00:14:02.200
So later, after the talk, we
have the so-called happy hour.

00:14:02.200 --> 00:14:05.200
Feel free to try the
Kavalan Distillery Select.

00:14:05.200 --> 00:14:07.390
When you look at the
color, you'll be amazed,

00:14:07.390 --> 00:14:12.070
and you won't think that it is
a single malt whisky matured

00:14:12.070 --> 00:14:14.890
in very old refill cask.

00:14:14.890 --> 00:14:19.930
And that is all to do with the
combination of quality new make

00:14:19.930 --> 00:14:20.950
and the heat of Taiwan.

00:14:20.950 --> 00:14:22.450
NATE GANA: Yeah,
the heat of Taiwan.

00:14:22.450 --> 00:14:24.760
I mean India, is producing
a lot too right now.

00:14:24.760 --> 00:14:25.600
IAN CHANG: That's
right, that's right.

00:14:25.600 --> 00:14:27.870
NATE GANA: It's such a unique
climate to be producing in.

00:14:27.870 --> 00:14:28.870
IAN CHANG: That's right.

00:14:28.870 --> 00:14:31.120
NATE GANA: So how did you
go from essentially zero

00:14:31.120 --> 00:14:34.545
bottles in 2005 to
500,000 bottles annually?

00:14:34.545 --> 00:14:35.920
Is that what you're
at right now?

00:14:35.920 --> 00:14:38.805
IAN CHANG: 500,000 is
actually the old number now.

00:14:38.805 --> 00:14:39.430
NATE GANA: Wow.

00:14:39.430 --> 00:14:42.538
IAN CHANG: So we now do
nearly one million bottles.

00:14:42.538 --> 00:14:44.080
NATE GANA: One
million per year, wow.

00:14:44.080 --> 00:14:44.580
IAN CHANG: Per year.

00:14:44.580 --> 00:14:46.210
But we still have
a long way to go.

00:14:46.210 --> 00:14:53.470
Yes, but I would say two very
unique qualities of Kavalan

00:14:53.470 --> 00:15:00.670
is that on the nose Kavalan
offers you that very refreshing

00:15:00.670 --> 00:15:06.390
and also very clean,
fruity, floral characters.

00:15:06.390 --> 00:15:09.080
But then on the palate,
Kavalan offers you

00:15:09.080 --> 00:15:12.000
a nice, natural
sweetness, but also

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:16.410
the creamy and oily
character on the palate when

00:15:16.410 --> 00:15:17.300
you drink the whisky.

00:15:17.300 --> 00:15:18.258
NATE GANA: [INAUDIBLE].

00:15:18.258 --> 00:15:20.610
IAN CHANG: So that makes
the whole experience

00:15:20.610 --> 00:15:21.870
really enjoyable.

00:15:21.870 --> 00:15:23.760
NATE GANA: Yes, and I agree.

00:15:23.760 --> 00:15:27.420
Because as a judge in the
spirit of competition recently,

00:15:27.420 --> 00:15:31.230
we tasted through 150 spirits
on the Friday and the Saturday,

00:15:31.230 --> 00:15:33.540
and then top 83
spirits on the Sunday.

00:15:33.540 --> 00:15:36.270
And we came out
with a $30 bourbon

00:15:36.270 --> 00:15:38.187
as the world winner of
the best whisky, right?

00:15:38.187 --> 00:15:39.187
IAN CHANG: That's right.

00:15:39.187 --> 00:15:42.030
NATE GANA: And so it beat out,
I think, 300 other whiskies

00:15:42.030 --> 00:15:43.110
overall.

00:15:43.110 --> 00:15:45.712
And you think to yourself
that, you know you think whisky

00:15:45.712 --> 00:15:47.920
or you think you know wine,
and you do a blind taste,

00:15:47.920 --> 00:15:49.200
and the $30 bottle comes out.

00:15:49.200 --> 00:15:50.730
So I think it's
important to have

00:15:50.730 --> 00:15:54.510
your quality in your high end
but also quality in a lower end

00:15:54.510 --> 00:15:57.630
price point that allows people
to get familiar with the brand,

00:15:57.630 --> 00:16:00.060
and then move their
category and their palette

00:16:00.060 --> 00:16:02.053
up to a higher place.

00:16:02.053 --> 00:16:03.720
What would you say
the favorite of yours

00:16:03.720 --> 00:16:06.660
is that you have produced?

00:16:06.660 --> 00:16:12.000
IAN CHANG: Within our
portfolio, every one of them.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:13.960
NATE GANA: That's cheating.

00:16:13.960 --> 00:16:16.740
IAN CHANG: I mean, it all
depends on the occasions

00:16:16.740 --> 00:16:22.420
and also depends on the
mood that you are in.

00:16:22.420 --> 00:16:24.840
For example, the one
in the middle here,

00:16:24.840 --> 00:16:26.700
this is our Kavalan classic.

00:16:26.700 --> 00:16:31.050
I think this is a very good
everyday drinking whisky.

00:16:31.050 --> 00:16:34.890
This is something that I have
in a decanter in my office.

00:16:34.890 --> 00:16:41.340
Whenever I go back to the office
to prepare for the next thing

00:16:41.340 --> 00:16:43.920
to do, whenever I
have a break, I always

00:16:43.920 --> 00:16:47.135
have a small drum
of the classic.

00:16:47.135 --> 00:16:47.760
NATE GANA: Wow.

00:16:47.760 --> 00:16:49.468
IAN CHANG: But then
if you like something

00:16:49.468 --> 00:16:55.020
that is all about
complexity harmony,

00:16:55.020 --> 00:17:00.110
just like another brand
called the H something.

00:17:00.110 --> 00:17:01.680
NATE GANA: Yeah.

00:17:01.680 --> 00:17:03.420
IAN CHANG: This is
our answer to that.

00:17:03.420 --> 00:17:04.128
NATE GANA: I see.

00:17:04.128 --> 00:17:06.359
IAN CHANG: So even though
this one is a single malt

00:17:06.359 --> 00:17:11.790
whisky, when you drink it,
you won't realize that this

00:17:11.790 --> 00:17:14.010
is a single malt whisky.

00:17:14.010 --> 00:17:17.400
You'll think that it is a
blend because it is so complex,

00:17:17.400 --> 00:17:20.400
with so many layers of flavors.

00:17:20.400 --> 00:17:25.710
Because in the
method of blending

00:17:25.710 --> 00:17:28.020
this particular
expression, we have

00:17:28.020 --> 00:17:32.370
used certain types
of casks to mimic

00:17:32.370 --> 00:17:33.792
the effect of grain whisky.

00:17:33.792 --> 00:17:34.500
NATE GANA: Right.

00:17:34.500 --> 00:17:37.860
IAN CHANG: And then combined
with other types of casks,

00:17:37.860 --> 00:17:41.190
it's like grain and malt
blended together, which

00:17:41.190 --> 00:17:43.200
is just like a blend whisky.

00:17:43.200 --> 00:17:46.500
So this is something
for our consumers

00:17:46.500 --> 00:17:50.220
to try if they want
complexity and also

00:17:50.220 --> 00:17:52.242
heavier weight in terms of body.

00:17:52.242 --> 00:17:52.950
NATE GANA: Right.

00:17:52.950 --> 00:17:53.992
IAN CHANG: Of the whisky.

00:17:53.992 --> 00:17:56.490
NATE GANA: So oddly enough,
I first learned about Kavalan

00:17:56.490 --> 00:17:57.630
here in Chicago.

00:17:57.630 --> 00:18:00.420
I went to Binny's, and I
saw this beautiful setup.

00:18:00.420 --> 00:18:01.950
And I thought, what is that.

00:18:01.950 --> 00:18:04.800
And so you see Kavalan
now everywhere,

00:18:04.800 --> 00:18:06.870
but one of the things
that is interesting

00:18:06.870 --> 00:18:08.370
that's been a
common misconception

00:18:08.370 --> 00:18:10.002
is the Solist line.

00:18:10.002 --> 00:18:10.710
IAN CHANG: Right.

00:18:10.710 --> 00:18:13.650
NATE GANA: So the Solist line
is sort of the higher end

00:18:13.650 --> 00:18:16.350
range of the casks that
they have at Kavalan,

00:18:16.350 --> 00:18:19.560
but one thing you've
noticed is that in America,

00:18:19.560 --> 00:18:21.810
none of the bottles
say Solist on it.

00:18:21.810 --> 00:18:24.810
Yet it is the identical
bottle without the writing.

00:18:24.810 --> 00:18:26.400
So maybe you can clear this up.

00:18:26.400 --> 00:18:27.030
IAN CHANG: Yes.

00:18:27.030 --> 00:18:31.440
So in addition to these
three that we see here,

00:18:31.440 --> 00:18:34.170
we have also another
series, which

00:18:34.170 --> 00:18:36.630
is called the Solist series.

00:18:36.630 --> 00:18:39.210
And what the Solists
series is about

00:18:39.210 --> 00:18:42.060
is that they are
all cask strength.

00:18:42.060 --> 00:18:46.640
Because in Taiwan, we
have many consumers.

00:18:46.640 --> 00:18:49.540
I would say the majority
of our consumers,

00:18:49.540 --> 00:18:53.040
they like to have their
whisky at cask strength.

00:18:53.040 --> 00:18:54.800
Can you believe it?

00:18:54.800 --> 00:18:55.950
Straight from the cask.

00:18:55.950 --> 00:18:56.788
So normally the--

00:18:56.788 --> 00:18:59.080
NATE GANA: Is that just
Taiwanese, or is that everybody

00:18:59.080 --> 00:19:00.150
in general?

00:19:00.150 --> 00:19:03.100
IAN CHANG: Taiwanese, and
also certain parts in Europe,

00:19:03.100 --> 00:19:03.600
as well.

00:19:03.600 --> 00:19:04.558
NATE GANA: Interesting.

00:19:04.558 --> 00:19:05.340
Yes.

00:19:05.340 --> 00:19:07.770
IAN CHANG: We have
a saying in Taiwan,

00:19:07.770 --> 00:19:10.860
"there is no such thing
as a strong alcohol, only

00:19:10.860 --> 00:19:11.730
weaker man."

00:19:11.730 --> 00:19:14.960
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:14.960 --> 00:19:15.690
No, I'm joking.

00:19:15.690 --> 00:19:19.042
NATE GANA: I'm going to put that
on a notepad, and put that up,

00:19:19.042 --> 00:19:20.250
and you look at it every day.

00:19:20.250 --> 00:19:23.740
IAN CHANG: So they like
to drink cask strength.

00:19:23.740 --> 00:19:30.060
And so it's all about
strength in the range of 53

00:19:30.060 --> 00:19:33.720
to some even as high as 59.

00:19:33.720 --> 00:19:40.110
So when we entered into the
US five or six years ago,

00:19:40.110 --> 00:19:43.830
we also want to enter the
Solis series into the US.

00:19:43.830 --> 00:19:46.620
But unfortunately we
were told that there

00:19:46.620 --> 00:19:49.800
has been another company,
they have already

00:19:49.800 --> 00:19:52.590
registered in the name Solist.

00:19:52.590 --> 00:19:53.597
Here in the US.

00:19:53.597 --> 00:19:54.180
NATE GANA: OK.

00:19:54.180 --> 00:19:57.540
IAN CHANG: So that's why it's
a pity that we cannot use

00:19:57.540 --> 00:19:58.320
the word Solist.

00:19:58.320 --> 00:19:59.237
NATE GANA: Understood.

00:19:59.237 --> 00:20:01.920
IAN CHANG: But if you go to
professional wine and liquor

00:20:01.920 --> 00:20:04.843
stores, like Binny's
and other ones.

00:20:04.843 --> 00:20:05.760
NATE GANA: Total Wine.

00:20:05.760 --> 00:20:06.260
IAN CHANG: That's right.

00:20:06.260 --> 00:20:07.540
Total Wine and so on.

00:20:07.540 --> 00:20:11.343
If you ask them for Solist, we
do have them here in the US.

00:20:11.343 --> 00:20:12.260
NATE GANA: You do, OK.

00:20:12.260 --> 00:20:14.468
IAN CHANG: It's just that
they are not called Solist.

00:20:14.468 --> 00:20:18.780
They are called, for example x
bourbon cask strength, or Vinho

00:20:18.780 --> 00:20:21.150
Barrique cask
strength, and so on.

00:20:21.150 --> 00:20:21.750
That's right.

00:20:21.750 --> 00:20:23.610
NATE GANA: Yeah,
because I'm from Canada,

00:20:23.610 --> 00:20:25.710
and in Canada we
have the Solist.

00:20:25.710 --> 00:20:27.793
So I saw it here, and
I thought, OK, well,

00:20:27.793 --> 00:20:28.710
that's the same thing.

00:20:28.710 --> 00:20:29.342
It has to be.

00:20:29.342 --> 00:20:31.050
Then I would look at
the labels, and they

00:20:31.050 --> 00:20:34.042
would have the same, or if
not higher, alcohol content.

00:20:34.042 --> 00:20:36.000
You know that's it's
going to be cask strength.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:37.583
It's going to be
from the Solist line.

00:20:37.583 --> 00:20:38.430
Interesting.

00:20:38.430 --> 00:20:41.550
So what's next for
Kavalan in terms

00:20:41.550 --> 00:20:43.470
of what you guys are producing?

00:20:43.470 --> 00:20:48.060
IAN CHANG: So the next for
Kavalan, as mentioned just now,

00:20:48.060 --> 00:20:51.750
we will produce also gins.

00:20:51.750 --> 00:20:57.060
And also for the future, I
think beer is another product

00:20:57.060 --> 00:20:57.740
we will produce.

00:20:57.740 --> 00:20:58.490
NATE GANA: Really?

00:20:58.490 --> 00:21:00.600
IAN CHANG: Yes, but
it's not called Kavalan.

00:21:00.600 --> 00:21:02.520
It's called something else.

00:21:02.520 --> 00:21:05.230
It's called [INAUDIBLE],,
[INAUDIBLE] beer.

00:21:05.230 --> 00:21:08.940
So I think King Car
company, once again,

00:21:08.940 --> 00:21:15.290
the company behind Kavalan, we
are thinking of moving forward

00:21:15.290 --> 00:21:20.870
into the future with more
and more alcoholic beverages,

00:21:20.870 --> 00:21:23.072
a bit similar to
a Suntory Japan.

00:21:23.072 --> 00:21:23.780
NATE GANA: Right.

00:21:23.780 --> 00:21:26.420
IAN CHANG: So in addition
to our non-alcoholic food

00:21:26.420 --> 00:21:28.400
and beverage, I
think Mr. Lee, he

00:21:28.400 --> 00:21:34.260
wants to go into the
alcoholic beverage industry.

00:21:34.260 --> 00:21:35.940
That's, I think,
our long term goal.

00:21:35.940 --> 00:21:37.440
NATE GANA: Interesting,
interesting.

00:21:37.440 --> 00:21:40.760
So what is the reason that you
guys have never produced an age

00:21:40.760 --> 00:21:42.155
statement whisky?

00:21:42.155 --> 00:21:45.040
IAN CHANG: Yes, this is
a very good question.

00:21:45.040 --> 00:21:47.930
We have consumers
asking us everyday,

00:21:47.930 --> 00:21:49.730
are we going to
produce whisky with age

00:21:49.730 --> 00:21:52.820
statement in the future.

00:21:52.820 --> 00:21:55.730
At this stage, I would say no.

00:21:55.730 --> 00:22:00.990
But having known Mr. Lee so
well, he's very unpredictable.

00:22:00.990 --> 00:22:05.220
So you never know in the
future if we will do it or not.

00:22:05.220 --> 00:22:07.580
But the thing is,
personally, I think it is not

00:22:07.580 --> 00:22:09.890
really necessary to do so.

00:22:09.890 --> 00:22:15.080
Once again, if you look at the
hot climate of Taiwan, which

00:22:15.080 --> 00:22:18.590
is subtropical, if you come
to Taiwan in the summertime

00:22:18.590 --> 00:22:22.610
between May and
October each year,

00:22:22.610 --> 00:22:25.070
it is normally 38
degrees Celsius, which

00:22:25.070 --> 00:22:26.972
I would say 90 Fahrenheit.

00:22:26.972 --> 00:22:27.680
NATE GANA: Right.

00:22:27.680 --> 00:22:29.010
IAN CHANG: Something like that.

00:22:29.010 --> 00:22:33.200
So our evaporation is
actually quite high.

00:22:33.200 --> 00:22:37.400
As you can imagine, if you
store your new make in a cask

00:22:37.400 --> 00:22:40.205
for, say, 15 or 20 years--

00:22:40.285 --> 00:22:40.910
NATE GANA: Yes.

00:22:40.910 --> 00:22:45.290
IAN CHANG: With 8% to 10%
evaporation each year,

00:22:45.290 --> 00:22:48.620
by the end of 20 years time,
you don't get much left.

00:22:48.620 --> 00:22:52.582
All you get left is something
that is very woody and also--

00:22:52.582 --> 00:22:53.540
NATE GANA: Makes sense.

00:22:53.540 --> 00:22:57.240
IAN CHANG: Out of balance in
terms of fruitiness, floral,

00:22:57.240 --> 00:22:57.740
and so on.

00:22:57.740 --> 00:23:01.470
Because when you drink whisky,
you want the whole package

00:23:01.470 --> 00:23:04.633
with the fullest
flavor and complexity.

00:23:04.633 --> 00:23:05.550
NATE GANA: Absolutely.

00:23:05.550 --> 00:23:07.133
IAN CHANG: But by
the end of 20 years,

00:23:07.133 --> 00:23:10.040
with so much evaporating
into thin air,

00:23:10.040 --> 00:23:11.390
I think we don't have much left.

00:23:11.390 --> 00:23:13.130
And also we lose the balance.

00:23:13.130 --> 00:23:13.760
NATE GANA: Yes.

00:23:13.760 --> 00:23:18.440
IAN CHANG: So unless we can
do it in a different way,

00:23:18.440 --> 00:23:22.550
but I think we cannot really
produce whisky with age

00:23:22.550 --> 00:23:23.152
statement.

00:23:23.152 --> 00:23:23.860
NATE GANA: Right.

00:23:23.860 --> 00:23:24.110
IAN CHANG: Yeah.

00:23:24.110 --> 00:23:25.550
NATE GANA: Well, I mean it
seems to be working for you

00:23:25.550 --> 00:23:26.633
without the age statement.

00:23:26.633 --> 00:23:28.820
IAN CHANG: Because
having said all this,

00:23:28.820 --> 00:23:30.410
it's not really
necessary either.

00:23:30.410 --> 00:23:35.750
Because when you try our whisky
later, like you have already

00:23:35.750 --> 00:23:38.310
is tried to whisky for
within the [INAUDIBLE]..

00:23:38.310 --> 00:23:40.640
NATE GANA: A lot of
your whiskies, yes.

00:23:40.640 --> 00:23:44.000
IAN CHANG: You noticed
that, even though whiskies,

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:47.490
they are matured for a
short period of time.

00:23:47.490 --> 00:23:51.350
But the maturity, the
complexity, they're

